<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,618,1254]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[151,273,618,643]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,618,643]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Body tapering towards both ends, fusiform. Tunic thick, becoming thicker ventrally. Cephalic cage chaetae long, mostly covered by fine papillae. Body papillae long, becoming longer in parapodial lobes. Notopodia and neuropodia ventrolateral. Notochaetae long, multiarticulated capillaries with short articles, visible distally; neurohooks mostly single per ramus, multiarticulated, crest entire. Free living.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,618,1254]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,763,787]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
This genus name includes the first few letters in 
<emphasis box="[896,1042,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1829" box="[896,1038,763,787]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabelligera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Flabelligera</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and the last name of Ernst Ehlers. He was an excellent polychaete taxonomist who not only made fine descriptions but also was an excellent artist. Further, his publications on Antarctic fauna are classic and in one of them, he described the 
<typeStatus box="[1213,1261,835,859]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
species for the genus. Gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,618,1254]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,907,931]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2012" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2012" box="[323,466,907,931]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabehlersia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus" status="n. g.">
<emphasis box="[323,466,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabehlersia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[474,524,907,931]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="genus">n. g.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1829" box="[675,815,907,931]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabelligera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[675,815,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because in both the body papillae are completely covered by the tunic, notochaetae are shorter than or as long as the body width, and the crests of neurohooks are thick and entire. These genera differ in the general body shape, the relative development of the anterior end, and parapodial position. Thus, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2012" box="[404,547,1014,1038]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabehlersia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[404,547,1014,1038]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabehlersia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the body is fusiform, the anterior end markedly tapers to a long, thin cone, and parapodia are displaced ventrally, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1829" box="[660,800,1051,1075]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabelligera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[660,800,1051,1075]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the body is truncate anteriorly, tapers posteriorly, and all parapodia are lateral.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,618,1254]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,294,1123,1147]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabehlersia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,294,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabehlersia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ehlers, 1897)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Ehlers" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[400,785,1122,1147]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabelligera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="induta" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[400,618,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Flabelligera induta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ehlers, E." box="[633,777,1122,1146]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref45766" refString="Ehlers, E. (1897) Polychaeten. Hamburger Magalhaensische Sammelreise. Friederichsen, Hamburg, 148 pp." type="book" year="1897">Ehlers, 1897</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[791,889,1122,1146]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Annenkova-Chlopina 1924)" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Annenkova-Chlopina" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[942,1408,1122,1147]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Flabehlersia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="persimilis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[942,1079,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">F. persimilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Annenkova-Chlopina, N." box="[1093,1400,1122,1146]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="125 - 128" refId="ref44671" refString="Annenkova-Chlopina, N. (1924) Neues uber die Verbreitung einger Arten der Polychaeten. Comptes Rendus de l'Academie des Sciences de Russie, 1924, 125 - 128." type="journal article" year="1924">Annenkova-Chlopina 1924</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The diagnostic features for the species are included in the key below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,618,1254]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1194,1219]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
The genus is bipolar because one species occurs in the Arctic Ocean and the other one in the Antarctic Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
